The world born of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists had taken control of four civilian aircraft. They launched two of the planes into the Twin Towers of the World Trade Center in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and crashed the fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another government building in Washington, D.C.
All the air pirates were originally from the Middle East, and 15 of them were from Saudi Arabia.
They had all been trained in Afghanistan, and four of them at American aviation schools, as part of an operation planned, organized, and carried out by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
At the end of the day, it was mourned that 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were American, though citizens from over a hundred other countries had also lost their lives.
At the time, many feared that September 11 had given birth to an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several explosions on Madrid's trains in March 2004, then the attack perpetrated on London's public transport in July 2005.
The terrorists who pledged allegiance to ISIS also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to ram into pedestrians).
Nevertheless, neither the United States nor any of their allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable magnitude to those of September 11 – which were without precedent.
Consequently, one must ask: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference has September 11 produced?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists have not succeeded in carrying out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have implemented control procedures that make it harder for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
The states have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, with terrorism constituting one of the few areas in which states that are often in disagreement are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not make a distinction between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
The translation of the given French sentence to English is:  "End the time when individuals and groups ready to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters."
It does not mean to say that terrorism has ceased to claim hundreds of thousands of lives every year.
However, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of current conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the September 11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
For example, Al-Qaeda survived the elimination of Ben Laden by American special forces in Pakistan nearly ten years after the September 11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of a new 9/11 cannot be ruled out either, despite the fact that the American government recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country existed domestically.
As formulated by the Provisional Irish Republican Army after its failed assassination attempt on British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today we did not have the luck, but remember that all it takes for us is to be lucky once."
The translation of the French sentence "Vous devrez en avoir toujours" into English is:  "You will always need it."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists could get their hands on nuclear material, or manage to develop and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
As of now, that is not the case.
September 11th nonetheless marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy in the last 20 years.
If the attacks did not lead to an era of global terrorism, they did indeed give rise to the famous war on terror, with significant consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way in which many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Soon after the September 11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who were then in control of the Afghan government, a choice: hand over the leaders of Al-Qaeda who were about to leave the country and were responsible for the September 11 attacks, or risk losing their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over the leaders of Al-Qaeda, American intelligence and military officials collaborated with an unstructured coalition of Afghan tribes, called the Northern Alliance, to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of the major part of the country.
However, this control was never total or uncontested.
Many loyal individuals to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda have sought refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they have gradually regained their strength and resumed their military operations against the government that had replaced them.
On their part, the United States have not sufficiently worked to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deny the Taliban sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead of doing so, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its height, the United States' intervention in Afghanistan mobilized over 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of operations has reached over $2 trillion, for more than 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence has deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban have proven more tenacious than America, which in 2020 had lost all willingness to fight in a conflict destined only for indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks have certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States were not, as President Richard Nixon had put it during the Vietnam War, a "giant impotent and contemptible."
This led some members of the administration (with Vice President Dick Cheney at the forefront) to refuse to take the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which it was believed the Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (as it turned out, most protagonists did not believe he actually had them).
Others wanted to spread democracy in Iraq, and then throughout the entire Middle East, believing that not only was this achievable, but it would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.
Triggered in March 2003, the Iraq War did not unfold as hoped or planned by the Bush administration, as well as by many Congressional members who had approved it (including Joe Biden, then a senator), and global leaders who supported it.
The United States were not prepared for the essentials of the events to come.
The military victories initially won did indeed allow for the government to be chased away, but they quickly gave way to widespread unrest and a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs worsened an already chaotic situation.
Fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, has demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to reinforce its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, in order to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable price.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but with a much higher human cost: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, far more wounded, and an exploding suicide rate among American military personnel (from Iraq as well as Afghanistan).
This total excludes, moreover, deaths among private contractors and Iraqis for whom estimates vary widely, but which number very certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other ways.
No evidence has ever shown Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for military intervention without UN approval – aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction – turned out to be based on no real foundation.
The images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, Iraq at war with itself has become synonymous with Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence in Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States were deeply engaged in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers present and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not and did not provide the United States with a compass in its foreign policy approach to a revived great power rivalry.
The wars waged in the aftermath of September 11 have also led to important internal consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with historically unprecedented predominant power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have meanwhile fueled opposition to a major and sustained global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this warlike propensity, linked to the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, severely impacted Americans' trust in elites, thereby fueling the rise of populist sentiments. Among other consequences, this contributed to Donald Trump's rise to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever domestically, and increasingly less willing to pursue this active form of foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has, for the most part, largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
With hindsight, we can now consider September 11 as a forewarning of what was to come: less about the globalization of terrorism than about the fears of globalization.
The attacks delivered the message that distance and borders mattered little in the era of globalization.
Nothing remains localized for long now, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis rooted in poor American financial management.
We are currently all confronted with a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, which itself is an accumulative effect of human activity releasing unprecedented amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events is coming to a close, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were rapidly chased from power; in recent weeks, they have reclaimed it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will revert to their old habits by once again becoming a sanctuary for terrorism, and if terrorists from around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, however, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that in turn already determines it.
